        {
            "id": "1fc96471266e45eaa4384",
            "questionText": "A construction crane has a pivot with a steel beam of mass $!$500$!$ $!$\\text{kg}$!$ located $!$12$!$ $!$\\text{m}$!$ horizontally from the pivot. To maintain rotational equilibrium, a counterweight is placed $!$5$!$ $!$\\text{m}$!$ from the pivot on the opposite side. Assuming a gravitational acceleration of $!$9.8$!$ $!$\\text{m/s}^2$!$, calculate the minimum mass (in $!$\\text{kg}$!$) required for the counterweight.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "a58bebce8ffa4681ac7b6",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that relates force, distance, and the turning effect (moment). Please select the correct formula for moment from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "7637f898-6bb7-44dc-9a1d-7c91f0ab93e7",
                        "c021eadd-5a2d-4fa7-bd9a-8c7c7cfb939c"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$M = F \\times d$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$M = F + d$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$M = \\frac{F}{d}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "2e3bdd08475546dcbc778",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now calculate the weight of the steel beam by using its mass and the gravitational acceleration. What is the force due to gravity acting on the beam?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4900"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "N",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "495dedb8-9a0b-42f1-9fc9-74b3a6f3a0cb"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "e3b335c7244c4571a6e95",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the weight you just found and the horizontal distance from the pivot to determine the moment produced by the beam. Multiply the weight by the distance to get the moment.",
